      "markdown": "# Revisiting the 2023 wildfire season in Canada \n\nFlavie Pelletier ${ }^{\\mathrm{a}, *}$, Jeffrey A. Cardille ${ }^{\\mathrm{a}}$, Michael A. Wulder ${ }^{\\mathrm{b}}$, Joanne C. White ${ }^{\\mathrm{b}}$, Txomin Hermosilla ${ }^{\\mathrm{b}}$<br>${ }^{a}$ McGill University, Department of Natural Resource Sciences, Sainte-Anne-de-Bellevue, Quebec, H9X 3V9, Canada<br>${ }^{b}$ Canadian Forest Service (Pacific Forestry Centre), Natural Resources Canada, 506 West Burnside Road, Victoria, British Columbia, V8Z 1M5, Canada\n\n## A R T I C L E I N F O\n\nKeywords:\nForest monitoring\nLand cover\nAboveground biomass\nLandsat\nSentinel-2\n\n\n#### Abstract\n\nThe area burned by wildfires in Canada in 2023 is unprecedented in historical records. To help ensure the safety of communities and support the mobilization of firefighting resources, rapid detection of areas affected by wildfires is required. Satellite data are ideally suited to provide near real-time wildfire information over large areas. At the same time, clouds, smoke, and haze can obscure the collection of observations from sensors typically used for mapping purposes. Established methods using coarse spatial resolution satellites (e.g., MODIS, VIIRS) rely upon the combination of daily revisit to enable the rapid and reliable detection of large active fires, in full or in part, and the application of modeling (including spatial buffering) to infer additional, yet still obscured, areas. While timely, these initial maps of wildfire-impacted areas do not capture small fires (those smaller than 200 ha ) and, importantly, are not intended to differentiate unburned areas within fire perimeters. To address these limitations, we used data from Sentinel-2A and -2B, and Landsat-8 and -9, which form a virtual constellation of four satellites to revisit and map burned area in Canada's forested ecosystems for the 2023 fire season. Availing upon the high temporal data density and using the Tracking Intra- and Inter-year Change algorithm (TIIC), an aggregate seasonal mapping of wildfires resulted in a total area affected by wildfires in 2023 of 12.74 Mha. Within this total area, 9.51 Mha of treed land cover was impacted. Shrubs and wetlands comprised most of the remaining non-treed area that was burned. Using a 2022 map of aboveground treed biomass (AGB), approximately 0.649 Pg of AGB was impacted by 2023 wildfires, representing an 11-fold increase in AGB impacts relative to a long-term annual average of treed AGB loss. Differences between the estimate of total burned area reported herein and the total burned area indicated by the Natural Resources Canada (NRCan) Fire M3 hotspot fire perimeters ( 18.64 Mha ) were analyzed. Overall, estimates of burned area differed by 5.9 Mha , including over 1.13 Mha of water identified as burned within the NRCan perimeters. Differences in land cover and AGB impacts between the two products were also investigated and quantified. TIIC enables the near-continuous capture of areas impacted by fire through the fire season, allowing for within-year refinement of total burned area, rapid interrogation of land cover types impacted, and estimation of associated biomass consequences.\n\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nWildfires have always been present over Canada's forested landscapes (Hanes et al., 2019; Stocks et al., 2002), with the 2023 fire season reported as the most spatially extensive ever documented, surpassing the previous record for total area burned of 7.6 Mha in 1989 (Natural Resources Canada, 2023). The main factors thought to have contributed to the unprecedented 2023 fire season in Canada were the extreme fire-weather conditions, including unusually low precipitation and the warmest May-July period since 1940 (Barnes et al., 2023), resulting in an abnormally long fire season (Kolden et al., 2024). Canada is expected\nto continue to experience intense fire seasons, as recent decades have highlighted the consequences of climate change on the lengthening of fire seasons and the increasing frequency of fire-prone weather conditions (Ahatzoglou et al., 2019; Jain et al., 2017; Jones et al., 2022). Climate change is expected to have a significant impact on northern forests in particular due to rapid and considerable temperature increases in this region (Price et al., 2013), as each additional degree of warming could lead to a tripling of burned area (Ali et al., 2012). Therefore, accurate reporting of the impacts of the 2023 fires in Canada is important for understanding how unusual the 2023 fire season was compared to the long-term trends in fire activity, and for understanding the long-term\n\n[^0]\n[^0]:    a Corresponding author.\n\n    E-mail address: flavie.pelletier@mail.mcgill.ca (F. Pelletier)."
    },
    {
      "markdown": "impacts on forests and surrounding communities (Boulanger et al., 2024).\n\nRapid detection of wildfires is essential to support the allocation of firefighting resources and ensure the safety of communities (Johnston et al., 2020). Optical satellite imagery has been demonstrated as an appropriate data source for near real-time mapping of active fires (hotspots) over remote and large spatial extents (Wooster et al., 2021), such as Canada's forests (Fraser et al., 2000), when not obscured by clouds, smoke, or haze (Flannigan and Haar, 1986). Active fires, even at sub-pixel levels, can be detected using remote sensing instruments that are sensitive to middle infrared wavelengths ( $\\sim 4 \\mu \\mathrm{~m}$ ). These detected hotspots can be merged using spatial proximity rules for aggregation (Fraser et al., 2000; Giglio et al., 2018) or be buffered to provide an estimate of burned areas that are obscured by smoke, haze, or cloud for generation of up-to-date estimates of burned area (Canadian Forest Service, 2022). Federally reported estimates of burned area in Canada are based upon the Fire Monitoring, Mapping and Modelling (Fire M3) daily hotspot mapping algorithm by Natural Resources Canada's (NRCan) Canadian Wildland Fire Information System (CWFIS; Englefield et al., 2004). Originally developed to utilize AVHRR imagery, later iterations of the algorithm have incorporated sensors with higher spatial resolution and improved radiometry and geometry, while maintaining a wide swath and frequent (daily) revisit, such as MODIS and VIRS. Due to the large pixels used, and ambiguity regarding the spatial location of actual hotspots, the resulting daily mapped fire perimeters are best suited for large fires (> 200 ha, https://cwfis.cfs.nrcan.gc.ca/background/dsm/fm3) and demonstrating trends rather than as a depiction of actual burned areas (White et al., 2017). As a heuristic, White et al. (2017) report an approximate expectation of a $40 \\%$ overestimation of burned area, based on a sample of large fires, from approaches using coarse spatial resolution satellite data (e.g., $1 \\mathrm{~km}^{2}$ ) compared to approaches using finer spatial resolution data (e.g., Landsat). Further, the larger the wildfire or the larger the number of fires, the greater the expectation for the overestimate in area. Fires coarsely mapped for short-term information needs can be further refined for long-term records and to meet the information needs associated with applications such as carbon accounting (Stinson et al., 2011). At the provincial level, the Canadian Interagency Forest Fire Centre (CIFFC) collects daily fire progression information from provincial fire agencies. Fire perimeters from provincial agencies can be derived from ground/airborne GPS, manual sketch mapping, or remotely-sensed imagery (e.g., satellite, aerial, digital camera), leading to variable accuracy (Skakun et al., 2022). At the end of the fire season the fire perimeters reported by provincial agencies are compiled in the Canadian National Fire Database (CNFDB).\n\nWhile not as timely as daily hotspot detection (Wooster et al., 2021), mapping of burned areas can be improved by using data from satellites with medium spatial resolution ( $10-100 \\mathrm{~m}$ ). Satellites such as Sentinel-2 and Landsat-8 and -9 are spectrally and spatially similar and form a virtual constellation when combined (Walder et al., 2015) enabling the acquisition of a unique image approximately every three days (Li and Roy, 2017). Multiple methods have been developed to map fires in Canada using time series of medium spatial resolution optical data (Hall et al., 2008; Hermosilla et al., 2015; Schroeder et al., 2011), often using the Normalized Burn Ratio (NBR; Key and Benson, 2006), or by combining satellite data with aerial survey information (Hall et al., 2020) to understand and calibrate historical burn records (Skakun et al., 2022). The latency associated with the complete generation of these burned area products may range from months to years, particularly for late-season fires, as imagery from the following year is often needed to accurately capture these events (Hall et al., 2020; White et al., 2014). Since 2004, Natural Resources Canada has produced the 30-m National Burned Area Composite (NBAC) in the year following each fire season, using mostly medium-resolution spatial imagery (Landsat, Sentinel-2), but also data directly from provincial agencies (Hall et al., 2020; Skakun et al., 2022). Considering all available products, the main challenge\nin accurate wildfire mapping remains the trade-off between spatial detail and timeliness. Wildfires can be rapidly detected using hotspot technology, but these methods do not accurately represent the actual burned area due to the nature of the data used and the processing applied (Fraser et al., 2000). Alternatively, medium-resolution optical imagery is often used to accurately map burned area, but only after the wildfire season has ended, resulting in a delay in the production of authoritative burned area maps (Skakun et al., 2022).\n\nTo limit the trade-off between spatial detail and timeliness, withinyear time series of medium spatial resolution imagery can be utilized. The imagery from the Sentinel-2 and Landsat virtual constellation is available via cloud access (notably, via Google Earth Engine) shortly after acquisition, providing multiple observations over short time intervals. This increases the probability of cloud- or smoke-free imagery and thus the ability to produce refined, near-real-time estimates of burned area, as changes for a given spatial extent can be mapped as a new image becomes available. The Tracking Intra- and Inter-year Change (TIIC) algorithm was developed to monitor forest change across Canada's forested ecosystems in near-real time by leveraging Sentinel-2A and -2B plus Landsat-8 and -9 (Pelletier et al., 2024). TIIC uses information from previous iterations of observations to self-optimize, resulting in an increasingly accurate mapping of burned areas at a spatial resolution that provides a detailed depiction of the location and extent of both large and small fires. This allows for rapid refinement of total burned area estimates and the generation of additional information on affected land cover types, including treed versus non-treed, and estimation of biomass loss.\n\nIn this study, we investigated the extent and impacts of the 2023 fire season using the near-real time TIIC algorithm (Pelletier et al., 2024). We mapped and calculated the total area burned in Canada's forested ecosystems in 2023, as well as the timing of these wildfires, the amount of aboveground biomass (AGB) affected, and the type of land cover impacted. We also compared compatible attributes between the TIIC burned areas with the fire perimeters and area estimates shared via NRCan's CWFIS and used supplemental information (i.e., land cover and AGB) to better understand the nature of the differences between the two map products. The novelty of the research presented herein in in demonstrating an approach that enables accurate mapping of burned area in a manner that is both spatially detailed and timely.\n\n## 2. Study area\n\nThe analysis is conducted for the entirety of Canada's forested ecosystems, which cover 650 Mha, and largely consist of treed areas (362 Mha, Natural Resources Canada, 2022), but also include extensive representation of wetlands, lakes, shrubs, and herbs. Canada's forested ecosystems are divided into 12 forest-dominated ecozones, following delineation reported in Stinson et al. (2011). Historically, wildfires in Canada have been concentrated in certain forest-dominated ecozones, such as the Boreal Shield West, Taiga Shield West, and Taiga Plains, where large areas typically burn annually (White et al., 2017, Fig. 1A). In contrast, the annual extent of fires is more limited in the Atlantic Maritime and Pacific Maritime ecozones. Before 2010, the Montane Cordillera was also burned at low rates, but over the past decade, this ecozone has been increasingly affected by severe fire seasons (e.g., the 2017 fire season; Crowley et al., 2019), with a significant increasing trend in area burned (Coops et al., 2018). Depending on the period of interest and data used, national estimates of average annual forest area burned range from 1.6 Mha (White et al., 2017) to 2.2 Mha (Skakun et al., 2022) to 2.5 Mha (Canadian Forest Service, 2022). In terms of land cover, on average $71 \\%$ of the area burned annually is covered by trees (Hermosilla et al., 2018) and 0.056 Pg out of a total of 27.32 Pg of AGB are estimated to burn annually (Walder et al., 2020)."
    },
