    },
    {
      "markdown": "### 3.1.2. NRCan fire data\n\nThe Fire Monitoring, Mapping, and Modeling System (Fire M3) from the CWFIS (Canadian Forest Service, 2022) identifies and maps actively burning fires (or hotspots) daily throughout the forest fire season using the latest MODIS and VIRS-I imagery, focusing on wildfires $>200$ ha (Fraser et al., 2000). These data are used as the basis for national reporting of active fires, and historical data are compiled in the Canadian National Fire Database (CNFDB; https://cwfis.cfs.nrcan.gc.ca/ha/ nfdb). During the 23 -week fire season, between April 26th and October 6th' 2023, 18.4 Mha over 6623 fires of all sizes were reported by provincial agencies (CIFFC), via the National Wildland Fire Situation Report (https://cwfis.cfs.nrcan.gc.ca/report). Fires $>200$ ha accounted for 822 of the 6623 fires, as compiled in the NRCan hotspot estimated perimeter database downloaded on October 11, and totalled 18.0 Mha of burned area. The 822 fire polygons (Fig. 1B) used for comparison in the analysis, were imported to Google Earth Engine, converted to a $30-\\mathrm{m}$ raster format and reprojected to a standard NAD83/Canada Lambert (EPSG: 3978) projection used for all the raster data included in this analysis. Non-spatial weekly estimates of area burned were obtained from the National Wildland Fire Situation report (https://cwfis.cfs. nrcan.gc.ca/report/graphs\\#gr4) to graph the timing of the cumulative burned area.\n\n### 3.1.3. Land cover data\n\nThe 2022 30-m land cover map for Canada's forested ecosystems was produced using the Virtual Land Cover Engine (VLCE) framework, which produces annual land cover maps based on the classification of Landsat spectral information, and environmental and topographic predictors, with temporal consistency informed by disturbances (Hermosilla et al., 2018, 2022). The VLCE comprises 12 land cover classes, including four that represent treed vegetation (coniferous, deciduous, mixedwood and wetland-treed). Assessment conducted with independent validation data resulted in an overall accuracy of $77.9 \\%$ (Hermosilla et al., 2022).\n\n### 3.1.4. Aboveground treed biomass data\n\nA 2022 30-m aboveground treed biomass map was produced following the methodology developed by Matasci et al. (2018b, 2018a), which integrated Landsat composite imagery with a comprehensive set of lidar plots using Nearest Neighborhood imputation to produce annual forest structure maps of Canada's forest ecosystems. The reported accuracy of the AGB maps, assessed using independent validation data, resulted in an $\\mathrm{R}^{2}$ of 0.699 , an RMSE $\\%$ of 65.8 , and a bias of -0.66 (Matasci et al., 2018a). To determine the impacts of the 2023 wildfires, we followed Pelletier et al. (2024) to use pixel-level estimates of AGB increment based on long-term data to project to a 2023 AGB expectation.\n\n### 3.2. Tracking Intra- and inter-year change\n\nFires in Canada's forested ecozones were monitored in near-real time using the Tracking Intra- and Inter-year Change (TIIC) algorithm (Pelletier et al., 2024) developed in Google Earth Engine (Gorelick et al., 2017). This algorithm enables the identification of stand-replacing disturbances based on a time series of images. To do this, TIIC builds an expectation time series from the spectral signature of a pixel from one or more years of images prior to the year of analysis, which is compared to new images that are acquired in near-real time (referred to as the target time series). The 2023 fire season was analyzed by building the expectation time series using spectral information from the 2021 and 2022 growing seasons from Sentinel-2A and -2B, Landsat-8, and Landsat-9 imagery. As new images are acquired and added to the target time series, TIIC calculates the probability of change for each pixel and identifies as candidate-changed pixels those that are typed as fire and have a probability of change greater than 0.5 . Changes were confirmed when the probability of change exceeded 0.3 , and the date associated with a\nburned pixel was then recorded. This recorded date of a burned pixel could be delayed from days to weeks depending on the availability of imagery and the presence of clouds, haze, or smoke. The recorded dates of burned pixels were resampled into 10-day time windows. Water bodies were excluded from the final burned pixels based on the water category in the land cover classification. Accuracy assessment using independent validation data showed a gradual increase in accuracy for the stand-replacing change class as additional images were added to the algorithm (from an initial producer's accuracy of $23 \\%$ at the beginning of the growing season to $98 \\%$ at the end of nine 10-day time windows), with a user's accuracy of $97 \\%$ (Pelletier et al., 2024). Moreover, the pixels assessed as having been burned had a user's accuracy and a producer's accuracy of $99 \\%$.\n\nChange pixels were grouped into two classes based on the detection period: summer fires and fall fires. Summer burned pixels were detected between May 30th and September 17th, and the fall burned pixels were detected between September 17th and October 25th. As a result, there are eleven summer 10-day time windows ( 110 days) and almost four time windows in the fall ( 38 days). For the summer fires, burned pixels were identified as changed and typed as fire by TIIC, independently of the NRCan perimeters. The fall period was added as an extension of the summer analysis period introduced in Pelletier et al. (2024), to allow for examination of the entire 2023 NRCan fire perimeter record. For the fall period, TIIC only detected changes within a $4-\\mathrm{km}$ buffer of the NRCan fire perimeters. This approach was used to limit commission errors that can arise due to known limitations of mapping with optical data during fall due to phenology, snow cover, or low sun angles (Huang et al., 2010).\n\n### 3.3. Comparison of TIIC and NRCan burned area estimates\n\nWe compared the results of the TIIC detection of burned area from the 2023 fire season with the results of the NRCan fire perimeters. Analyses were conducted for Canada's forested ecosystems and stratified by forest ecozone. We calculated the total area burned and the area burned by land cover class to better understand the impact of wildfires on land cover. We also calculated the AGB impacted by the wildfires for each product. Burned pixels were assumed to result in almost complete or eventual depletion of AGB, so the AGB values associated with burned pixels were summed to obtain the total AGB loss. Finally, we analyzed the temporal correspondence of the area burned detected by comparing the timing of the TIIC burned pixels to the reported non-spatial weekly estimates described above.\n\n## 4. Results\n\n### 4.1. Area burned\n\nFor the 2023 fire season, the TIIC algorithm detected 12.74 Mha of burned area in Canada's forested ecozones (Table 1, Fig. 2), representing $1.8 \\%$ of the total forest-dominated ecozone area. Of the 12.74 Mha , 11.57 Mha ( $90.9 \\%$ ) was burned by summer fires, and 1.16 Mha ( $9.1 \\%$ ) by fall fires (Table 2). The ecozones with the largest area burned were the Taiga Plains ( 3.51 Mha ), followed by the Taiga Shield East ( 2.33 Mha ), Boreal Plains ( 1.93 Mha ), Taiga Shield West ( 1.23 Mha ) and Boreal Shield East ( 1.22 Mha ). The Atlantic ( 0.02 Mha ) and Pacific Maritime ( 0.07 Mha ) ecozones were the least affected by wildfires. In comparison, the NRCan fire perimeters mapped a total of 18.64 Mha of burned area. The largest burned area was reported in the Taiga Plains ( 5.23 Mha ), Boreal Plains ( 3.29 Mha ) and Taiga Shield East ( 2.62 Mha ). The area burned by the NRCan fire perimeter ranged from 1.12 times (Taiga Shield East) to 1.71 times (Boreal Plains) greater than that detected by TIIC (Fig. 3), except in the Pacific Maritime. The largest differences in burned area between TIIC and NRCan were found in those ecozones that experienced more fires (i.e., Boreal Plains, Taiga Shield West, Montane Cordillera). This trend was not found in the Pacific"
