 the 2023 fire season ( $3.33 \\%$ of total AGB), while with the TIIC algorithm, the estimated AGB loss was 0.65 Pg ( $2.30 \\%$ of total AGB). The largest AGB losses from the TIIC results were reported for the Taiga Plains (203.52 Tg or $9.55 \\%$ of the ecozone total) and Boreal Plains ( 162.43 Tg or $4.05 \\%$ ). Although the amount of AGB burned was smaller in the Taiga Shield East ( 54.27 Tg ) and Taiga Shield West ( 41.42 Tg ), relative to the ecozone, the Taiga Shield East lost $4.59 \\%$ of the AGB and Taiga Shield West lost $6.30 \\%$. In contrast, AGB losses were minimal in the Atlantic Maritime ( 1.06 Tg ), Pacific Maritime ( 1.85 Tg ) and Taiga Cordillera ( 2.56 Tg ).\n\n### 4.4. Timing of burned pixels\n\nThe area burned across the season for TIIC shows that the burned area steadily increased throughout the summer, up until mid-September (Fig. 6), which usually coincides with the end of the fire season in Canada (Coogan et al., 2020). The weekly reporting for NRCan started when the first hotspots were detected (April 26 in 2023), with more spatially extensive burning starting two weeks later. The total burned area reported by NRCan rose steadily throughout the fire season, as well as the burned area detected by TIIC. The larger the burned area increments reported by NRCan, the larger the divergence between TIIC\n\nTable 3\nEcozone-level summaries and totals for Canada's forested ecosystems of aboveground biomass (AGB) loss during the 2023 fire season.\n\n| Ecozone | Total AGB <br> 2022 (Tg) | NRCan |  | TIIC |  |\n| :--: | :--: | :--: | :--: | :--: | :--: |\n|  |  | AGB <br> loss <br> (Tg) | AGB loss <br> (\\% of <br> ecozone) | AGB <br> loss <br> (Tg) | AGB loss <br> (\\% of <br> ecozone) |\n| Atlantic <br> Maritime | 1501.01 | 1.35 | 0.09 | 1.06 | 0.07 |\n| Boreal <br> Cordillera | 1741.26 | 17.50 | 1.01 | 14.53 | 0.83 |\n| Boreal Plains | 4014.21 | 260.01 | 6.48 | 162.43 | 4.05 |\n| Boreal Shield <br> East | 5883.92 | 80.99 | 1.38 | 60.88 | 1.03 |\n|