      "markdown": "![img-5.jpeg](img-5.jpeg)\n\nFig. 6. Cumulative area burned per 2023 date for all of Canada's forested ecozones based on the Tracking Intra- and Inter-year Change (TIIC) algorithm and the weekly burned area reported by Natural Resources Canada (NRCan).\n\n## 5. Discussion\n\nHerein, we used the TIIC change detection algorithm to map the areas impacted in the 2023 wildfire season at a 30-m spatial resolution and quantified the land cover impacts and the AGB consequences of these fires. Landsat and Sentinel-2 satellites provide medium spatial resolution imagery, based upon individual satellite revisit frequency, enabling TIIC to map wildfires throughout the fire season and at a management-relevant scale, limiting the trade-offs between scale and timeliness. Our results showed that more land burned in Canada during the 2023 wildfire season than in any other year since record-keeping began (Coops et al., 2018; Hanes et al., 2019; Stocks et al., 2002; White et al., 2022), exemplifying forecasted wildfire-related trends, including a lengthening of the fire season, a greater number of large\nfires, and an increase in the burned area (Hanes et al., 2019).\nTo undertake meaningful comparisons, it is prudent to match total burned areas derived from similar data sources. The TIIC burned areas are perhaps most analogous with the NBAC, because they utilize similar data sources, mostly Landsat and Sentinel-2. However, the 2023 areas cannot be compared as the 2023 NBAC was not yet available at time of writing. This does however highlight the latency that the TIIC algorithm addresses by providing near real-time medium spatial resolution wildfire information. NBAC is intended to provide a consistent, and refined estimate of burned area nationally, and the production of such a curated product requires time and effort to generate (Hall et al., 2020). There is a gap therefore wherein a product such as that derived from the TIIC algorithm can provide more rapidly refined estimates of area burned and associated consequences. Accounting for images acquired up to October 25, TIIC identified 12.74 Mha of land that was burned during the 2023 wildfire season, compared to the previous high of 6.65 Mha (Skakun et al., 2022) that was reported as burned in 1989 in the NBAC, which represents almost a 2-fold increase. More generally, the 12.74 Mha of burned area is 7.96 times greater than the Landsat-based long-term annual average burned area of 1.6 Mha (Coops et al., 2018; White et al., 2017). Differences in area burned are expected when comparing TIIC burned area to NRCan fire perimeters, as both the intended use and the data sources used to generate the products are different. There are trade-offs associated with both products. NRCan fire perimeters are a daily examination of active fires at a coarse spatial resolution, while TIIC maps burned areas within days to weeks at a fine spatial resolution. Despite their different characteristics and resolution, both products successfully detect burned areas at the same locations, as demonstrated by their agreement of 11.02 Mha of burned area. This comparison highlights the value of TIIC as an additional intra-year detection tool as it operates on a similar time frame (within a growing season) as the NRCan fire perimeters, but with finer spatial resolution.\n\nDuring extreme fire seasons like the one Canada experienced in 2023, fire management agencies focus on rapid-response and safety\n![img-6.jpeg](img-6.jpeg)\n\nFig. 7. TIIC area burned (Mha) per 10-day temporal window starting on May 30, 2023 for each ecozone. Ecozones are ordered from smallest to largest burned area based on TIIC. Note the different ranges of values on each $y$-axis."
    },
    {
      "markdown": "priorities. This need for timely information can necessitate the use of data and models that meet the short-term need such as the NRCan fire perimeters that are usually available within 24 h of a hotspot detection. However, these methods tend to lead to an overestimation of the burned areas, such as through inclusion of unburned islands or water bodies (Skakun et al., 2021; Walker et al., 2018; White et al., 2017). The overestimation of area can have consequences for applications such as carbon accounting, leading to identification of the need for more spatially refined estimates of burned area (Stinson et al., 2011). The NBAC product was developed to improve the determination of burned area (Hall et al., 2020) and to inform Canada's carbon budget modeling activities (de Groot et al., 2007), retrospectively providing refined estimates and products for operational programs. Past research has shown that the difference between the burned areas mapped using more refined approaches and those reported in the CNFDB increases as the total burned area increases (White et al., 2017). Our results indicate that the total burned area initially reported for Canada in 2023 ( 18.4 Mha ) is much larger than the actual area burned. The total burned area we mapped was 12.74 Mha , including 11.02 Mha that was also captured by the NRCan perimeters, which is $59 \\%$ of the burned area included in the NRCan fire perimeters ( 18.64 Mha ). This result is comparable to that reported by White et al. (2017), who found a $61 \\%$ overlap between their burned area and the burned area reported by the CNFDB for high burn years when considering a sample of large fires that accounted for at least $50 \\%$ of the area disturbed by wildfire in a given year. Our results for a census of all fires in a single fire year support and extend the findings of White et al. (2017), by showing that the overestimation does not only apply to large fires, but across fires of all sizes on average. Acknowledging that the burned area maps produced by TIIC are not perfect, the accuracy assessment of the methods applied herein to the same area for 2019 demonstrated that the mapped burned areas were reliably identified by the end of the fire season ( $98 \\%$ producer's accuracy, $97 \\%$ user's accuracy; Pelletier et al., 2024). Considering that the current estimate reported by NRCan includes more than 1 Mha of water bodies (Fig. 5), and that the burned area is expected to be overestimated on an annual basis ( $\\sim 43.8 \\%$; White et al., 2017), and given the comparison to previous mapping exercises with more spatially detailed sources of satellite data (Hermosilla et al., 2018; Skakun et al., 2021; White et al., 2017), we suggest that the actual burned area is likely closer to the 12.74 Mha reported herein than the 18.64 Mha estimated by the NRCan perimeters.\n\nUnderstanding the impacts of fires upon land cover is important as vegetation recovery will vary depending on the severity of a fire as well as what burned (White et al., 2022). Generally, large fires tend to occur in more northern and less productive forests, which lengthens the recovery, but the land cover class associated with the burned area also influences that rate of recovery (Madoui et al., 2015; White et al., 2022). Non-treed vegetation, which represented $25 \\%$ of the overall burned area based on the TIIC algorithm, generally recovers more quickly than treed vegetation (White et al., 2022). Within the treed vegetation, coniferous forests, which were the most affected by wildfires due to their flammability (Parisien et al., 2023), take longer to recover than broadleaf or mixedwood that can re-establish quickly post-fire (Bartels et al., 2016; White et al., 2022). Similarly, it has been shown that post-fire recovery varies per ecozone (White et al., 2022). The Taiga Shield East ( 2.33 Mha burned) and the Taiga Shield West ( 1.23 Mha burned) are the slowest to recover following wildfires (White et al., 2017, 2022White et al., 2022). Based upon the spatial resolution of the imagery utilized, the TIIC algorithm can map fires smaller than 200 ha, which represent a large proportion of the overall fires every year (Hanes et al., 2019). Even if the total annual area burned by small fires is minor when compared with that of large fires, there is value in capturing those smaller burned areas since they comprised a majority (by number) of wildfires in Canada and are therefore key to understanding fire regime variability (Hanes et al., 2019) and overall impacts of wildfire on forest ecosystems.\n\nAGB is a critical reservoir of forest carbon, and reporting AGB in addition to the area burned provides further context regarding the\nimpact of a fire as the relationship between the two is non-linear (Wulder et al., 2020). Our results show that an estimated 649 Tg of treed AGB, representing $2.3 \\%$ of the total treed AGB of Canada's forested ecozones, was impacted during the 2023 fire season. This was $36 \\%$ less treed AGB than was impacted using the NRCan perimeters, which were associated with a loss of 942 Tg . To contextualize the AGB loss associated with TIIC, Wulder et al. (2020) reported an annual rate of AGB loss due to wildfire of 56 Tg for the period between 1985 and 2016 and an overall loss for the same period of 1790 Tg . Therefore, the AGB loss from the 2023 fire season was an 11-fold increase over that longer-term annual average. Biomass change can be considered as constrained to the presence of disturbance or as part of an ecosystem-wide process of punctual and large losses over small areas concurrent with gradual and small increases of larger areas. While the areas differ, when assessing more broadly over the entire forested ecosystem, growth and biomass uptake for undisturbed areas historically has been about the same as the losses constrained to disturbed areas (Wulder et al., 2020), including for 2023 and the large burned area.\n\n## 6. Conclusion\n\nWe demonstrated the capacity to map burned areas at a 30-m spatial resolution in near-real time from multiple sensors for the 2023 fire season. The TIIC mapping approach provides a means to avail upon cloud data processing to enable the generation of low latency mapping of burned area. These multisource estimates can also be used to provide insights on the land cover types impacted by wildfires, as well as the treed AGB consequences. Moreover, the spatial detail captured by TIIC offers a reasonably rapid means to refine annual burned area estimates for assessing impacts. Initial estimates of burned area have been demonstrated to overestimate burned areas in large fire years, typically by $\\sim 40 \\%$ on an annual basis, with a latency before refined estimates can be generated from higher spatial resolution remotely sensed data. For 2023, this meant a difference of about 5.9 Mha , partially based upon mapping 1.12 Mha of water as burned area. Moving forward, parallel and complementary sets of remote sensing activities can be implemented to inform important short-term emergency planning information needs via established hotspot approaches with concurrent analysis of a dense time series of within-year imagery to provide spatially detailed and revised map products and related area estimates.\n\n## CRediT authorship contribution statement\n\nFlavie Pelletier: Writing - original draft, Visualization, Software, Methodology, Formal analysis, Conceptualization. Jeffrey A. Cardille: Writing - review \\& editing, Supervision, Methodology, Conceptualization. Michael A. Wulder: Writing - review \\& editing, Conceptualization. Joanne C. White: Writing - review \\& editing, Conceptualization. Txomin Hermosilla: Writing - review \\& editing, Conceptualization.\n\n## Declaration of competing interest\n\nThe authors declare that they have no known competing financial interests or personal relationships that could have appeared to influence the work reported in this paper.\n\n